postcontent: This rifle was built by red hawk custom shop in Colorado. It is a Remington 700 action with a 26" bull barrel cambered in 7mm-08. The 7mm-08 is a cartridge born from the 308 necked down to .284. There are a few great advantages to this the bullets used will have a higher BC( ballistic coefficient ). Which means the bullet flies farther, straighter, truer, greater velocity, high energy, and less recoil. It is ballistically far superior to the .308. I was able to shoot 3/4 moa with un-tuned loads very easily this is a 1/2 moa gun at 100 yards easily. It is set in a bell and Carlson A5 completely adjustable stock comb height, length of pull, and cant. Red hawk also installed a badger ordinance enlarged bolt knob, a talley 20 moa picatinny scope mount, lapped the bolt lugs, and tuned the trigger. This action is slick has been well taken care has only had 200 down the pipe. It comes with 1lb of imr4350, 40 rds of ammo, a set of RCBS dies, and assorted bullets

title: For Sale:  Made in 1900 Schmidt-Rubin Model 1889 96/11. 7.5x55 Swiss
postcontent:
Made in 1900 Schmidt-Rubin Model 1889 96/11. Chambered in 7.5x55 Swiss. 100% matching numbers including the sporterized stock. Harris Bi pod. Swiss Products offset scope mount. The ONLY non invasive scope mount made for the 96/11. This mount was $125+ shipping. Custom 1 off leather cheek bump/riser. Less riser, more bump to take the offset scope mount into consideration for a positive cheek weld. Basic Tasco 3-9x40 scope is holding up and is accurate out to 300 yards. If you want precision at 300+ meters, get a 'real' scope for this and you'll be unstoppable. The iron sights start at 300 meters, graduated to 2000 meters. It's also wearing a limbsaver recoil pad, but that can come off very easily. 

Price $525 Firm. No trades, I'm selling to get a PSL 54C.

The stamps document the history of this old shooter. It has been through the arsenal 3 separate times for each of the model upgrades it's gone through. I have everything written down here somewhere. I'll include my notes with the sale.

History:
Barrel Length - 30.7 inches: 4-groove, RH, concentric rifling, 1 in 10.63" 
(approx 6000 96/11s had a twist rate of 1 in 9") 
Overall Length - 51.2 inches 
Weight - 9.94lbs empty 
Action - Schmidt-Rubin Straight Pull 
Caliber - 7.5x55 Swiss (GP11) 
Capacity - 6 round detachable box magazine 
Sights - Tangent-leaf sight graduated to 2000m 
Total Production : 135,770 
Bayonet: Models 1889,1899 & 1906 

As early as 1903 there discussion about the adoption of a lighter, easier to handle rifle, with increased velocity cartridges. It had been determined that there were severe ballistic shortcomings to the 89/96 action /GP90 cartridge combination. In late 1907, the Swiss Rifle Commission gave permission to Waffenfabrik Bern to create 200 rifles for testing purposes. The rifle were built with the following configurations:

fifty rifles with 1889/96 Barrels firing GP90 cartridges, 
fifty rifles with 1889/96 Barrels firing GP90 cartridges, and re-milled cartridge chamber, fifty rifles with 1889/96 Barrels and new cartridges and re-milled cartridge chamber, 
fifty rifles with new barrels and new cartridges

Other modifications included the removal of the magazine cut-off, improved sights, and an integral rifle rest. While the integral rifle rest was discarded as superfluous, the testing otherwise proved successful.. This led to the authorization of the creation of 900 Rifles and 100 Carbines, for the purposed of testing the new GP08 (later redesignated GP11) cartridge. The 1908 Rifles and Carbines were fitted with Model 1889/1900 style 6 round magazines, and improved sights. The 1908s also had several unique features, not found in other Schmidt-Rubin models. The locking lug sleeve of the 1908’s bolt had three circular holes, presumably for weight savings purposes. In addition, the relief cuts on the top of 1908s receiver were of different length, with the longer cut set along the center of the receiver, with the shorter cut off to the side. On all other Schmidt-Rubins, the relief cuts were of equal length, and both cuts were equally offset from the centerline of the receiver.

By around 1907, the Swiss knew the old GP90 cartridge was inferior to those being adopted by their neighbors. So they started testing a new round. They built the 1908 series for this purpose. The 1908 has some unique feature, not seen in other Schmidt-Rubins, including three holes in the bolt. Testing showed the VGP08 cartridge produced significantly better results than the GP90 cartridge. Consequently, the VGP08 cartridge was adopted as the GP11 cartridge.

It was determined that the 89/96 could easily be converted (Model 1889s could not) to handle the new cartridge by re-barreling the rifle.

1889/96s were converted to 1896.11s buy replacing or modifying the following:

A new barrel was added. 
Already fitted the the barrel were new front and rear sights.
A pistol grip was grafted onto the stock of the rifle.
The new rifles were also fitted with 6rd magazines, similar to the 1889/1900 pattern magazine, minus the reinforcing ridge, although the magazine did include a bolt hold-open feature for when the magazine was empty.
A new trigger-guard was fitted to accommodate the new magazine. 

However, it took several years for all the 89/96s to be converted to 96/11 and 1911 Rifle production continued until 1918. Rather than leave large numbers of troops unarmed while the rifles were shipped off for conversion, they were re-issued Model 1889s. (Troops with Model 89/00 Short Rifles and 05 Carbines were re-issued 1893 Carbines).

Swiss soldiers are roughly classified into two categories, elite and reserve. Elites are under the age of 30, reserves are over the age of 30. Any trooper reaching reserve status, whom had a 89/96 during the changeover period was issued a Model 1889, and kept it for the remaining term of his service. Raw recruits, were issued Model 1889s as well at this point in time, and were later issued 96/11s or 1911s.

The various Canton Arsenals were given different priorities regarding when they were re-equipped. However, I'm not sure what those priorities were.

title: For Sale:  WINCHESTER Model 62 A 62A 22 Lr with ORIGINAL BOX         LNIB 22LR 1957 Pump Action Rifle
location: West Virginia, OK, TX., Mississippi, United States
postcontent:
FOR SALE! This listing is for a Winchester Model 62A pump action 22lr rifle. Serial Number 372645 manufactured approx 1957. FEATURES: 23" round Barrel, and exposed hammer. CONDITION: Excellent this is one of the nicest we have seen. Minor wear on the slide areas, a couple of marks in the stock all of which are shown in the photos. 
Original owner was elderly (my grand father) and did not know it was a valuable gun I will provide the history I know about it with the rifle. Box has been authenticated by numerous collectors is in nice shape showing age dated 55, tape is old that is on it, it has a price hand written on the outside which looks like it could be removed if wanted, paperwork is also nice. We have seen plenty of reproduction boxes, they are fairly easy to identify and rarely have the correct base markings and show the correct aging, if this one is not correct its fooled a lot of guys, this rifle has been displayed at two collector shows and not one person has claimed an issue. If you have been looking for a collector grade Model 62 they just do not get much nicer than this.  I usually answer emails in the mornings and evenings. The shipping amount is posted on this listing and will be in addition to the amount you bid or the buy now price.
The firearms must ship to a FFL Dealer or if the firearm qualifies I will accept Western Union transfer ONLY. I can ship your purchase within 48 hours of receipt of verified funds. This means the payment you send must clear our bank first. We are a FFL Licensed Dealer and we will include a copy of our FFL License with a firearm purchase to your dealer of choice.  I have no reason to mislead you nor do I want angry customers. Sales are final and sold AS IS unless approved by me. I do not offer any inspection periods.The firearms should be checked over by your Gunsmith prior to being shot or handled.  PLEASE know your own state and local laws prior to bidding. I will not modify any weapon to make it legal for your state. I will ship to all states if you have a FFL Dealer who will receive the item as it is listed without modification or disassembly.
ONLy serious buyer. Thanks.
